{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11381"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11381"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.35,0.29,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90605"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4026"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4609"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40023"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42583"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43219"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90605"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man is admitted to the hospital with a non-infective exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). Other than COPD he has a past medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and mild obesity. He reports an increase in cough frequency as well as shortness of breath and wheezing for several days. On examination, he is found to be speaking in short sentences with a generalised, widespread wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn arterial blood gas (ABG) is performed and shows the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaO2 - 65 mmHg (90 - 110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPaCO2 - 58 mmHg (35 - 45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH - 7.31 (7.35 - 7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 - 24 mmol/L (22 - 31)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate - 0.75 mmol/L (0.5 - 1.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is started on nebulised salbutamol, ipratropium and oral prednisolone. Over the following hours, his condition improves, his shortness of breath and wheeze has resolved, and he feels much better. On examination, he is haemodynamically stable and afebrile. A repeat ABG is performed and shows the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPO2 - 85 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPCO2 - 44 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH - 7.40\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3 - 26 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate - 3.85 mmol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be responsible for the worsening parameter found on the latest ABG?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypoxia","Respiratory muscle fatigue","Salbutamol","Gliclazide","Sepsis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELactate or lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic respiration. It is used clinically as a marker of hypoxia or poor tissue perfusion. Lactate levels greater than 2 mmol/L are known as hyperlactatemia, while levels greater than 4 mmol/L are known as lactic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECauses of elevated lactate can be classified using the Cohen and Woods system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType A lactic acidosis are caused by anaerobic muscle activity, hypoxia, poor tissue perfusion or poor oxygen delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType B lactic acidosis is further subdivided into type B1, lactic acidosis caused by disease states, and type B2, which is lactic acidosis caused by medications. Type B3 lactic acidosis is due to inborn errors of metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECauses of type B1 lactic acidosis include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELeukaemia, lymphoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInfection\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPancreatitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThiamine deficiency and short bowel syndrome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver failure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal failure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedications and substances that can cause type B2 lactic acidosis include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeta-agonists (salbutamol, formeterol, adrenaline)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBiguanides (metformin)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECyanide\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-retroviral agents\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParacetamol\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESalicylates (aspirin)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeta-agonists, such as salbutamol are frequently associated with elevated lactate. The mechanism is unclear but may be due to adrenergic-induced glycolysis, which leads to pyruvate accumulation which is converted to lactate. Furthermore, by activating the sodium-potassium ATPase pump, salbutamol may lead to increased ATP expenditure and a switch to anaerobic respiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoxia\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Erespiratory muscle fatigue\u003C/strong\u003E are possible causes of hyperlactatemia however this patient\u0027s clinical condition is improving, with increasing PO2 and decreasing pCO2, so this is less likely. Likewise, he is displaying no clinical symptoms or signs of \u003Cstrong\u003Esepsis\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EGliclazide\u003C/strong\u003E is not a known cause of hyperlactatemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Medications such as salbutamol may be associated with elevated lactate"],"references":["Dodda VR, Spiro P. Can albuterol be blamed for lactic acidosis? (0020-1324 (Print)).","Lau E, Mazer J Fau - Carino G, Carino G. Inhaled \u03b2-agonist therapy and respiratory muscle fatigue as under-recognised causes of lactic acidosis. LID - 10.1136/bcr-2013-201015 [doi] LID - bcr2013201015. (1757-790X (Electronic))."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11381"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74816"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T12:50:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-30T10:07:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4026"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90605"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id"